Details.module: TLO 3: State the Purpose and Description of the APM

Contents.Text:
• The APM provides storage and eject pressure for AUR Launch
• APM provides the interface between the AUR+C and WCS
The Advanced Payload Module (APM) provides structural support and enables interface between the All-Up-Round plus Canister (AUR+C), the Missile Tube, and the APM Support Service Equipment.

• The APM provides retention hardware for the AUR+C, all cabling and piping, and the APM itself.
• The Eject System consisting of the flask, eject valves, and downstream piping provides the energy necessary to eject the All Up-Round (AUR) from the Navy Canister during a launch event.

Contents.Text:
The Upper Support Plate serves the following functions:
• Primary structural interface to the host platform
• Structural backbone of the APM
• Direct interface between APM & Canisters
• Support and mounting for various sensors, brackets, & piping
• Seal outside environment from host platform
• Interface for Canister Onload/Offload Support Equipment
• Main interface for APM Lifting & Handling operations

• Shock Plates are a core part of APM structure that support Canister and Eject systems
• Provide radial support during shock event
• Provide mounting provisions for various APM & Eject Hardware
• All shock plates made from same rough machined model, 7127950X

• The Purpose of the Jacking Feet is to laterally stabilize the APM within the platform missile tube (LMVLS).
• The Jacking Feet act to support the APM during both operational and shock loading.
• The Jacking feet are deployed radially upon platform installation and retracted in the same manner during platform withdrawal.
